    <h3>My Role</h3>
    <p>When I started at Healthentic my title was UX/Product Manager. I was employee number 13, so I really got to define my roll and learn my way into a good fit. It was exciting, intimidating, and challenging all at once. I had the awesome opportunity to work on product and design strategy, be immersed in an Agile/Scrum development cycle, serve as product owner, build lots of prototypes, interview customers, and manage the UX process along side a very smart, talented team. I led much of the UX projects for the Population Health Dashboard product and surrounding product and design efforts.</p>
 
    
    <h3>Problem</h3>
    <p>Anyone who has done user experience work in an Agile/Scrum environment knows how difficult it can be to size, scope, and fit design work and deliverables into a precise cycle. The paradox is that user-centered design approaches are very much iterative; I&rsquo;ve found that the challenge is getting to the big picture through the short incremental cycles of the development process.</p>

    <p>I was certain our team could build products that technically worked and would be functionally usable. But how do we really focus on <em>experience</em>? This challenge is pervasive, evidenced by the abundance of training and workshops aimed at helping designers assimilate! To boot, Healthentic built health informatics products aimed at non-technical people. This meant getting to viability and feasibility&mdash;let alone everything we wanted focus on&mdash;wasn&rsquo;t always easy. Three tactics that were effective for the Healthentic team was to get ahead, test early and often, and go light on documentation.</p>

    <h3>Process</h3>
    <p>I followed a basic process, but there were often new problems that required new approaches. With such a wide variety of tools in the UX toolbox, it always made sense to pull out the best tool possible for the job at hand. Nonetheless, I established a general approach that we followed which started with getting at least two sprints ahead of the development team. And there were many cases we had to be working ahead by months, if not more.</p>

    <h4>Getting Ahead</h4>
    <p>Getting ahead meant we had to have a good view into the product road map and strategy. I participated with the other designers and product managers in reviewing the road map and developing a high-level game plan to deliver prioritized items. We would start by building a work plan for each project or milestone (Healthentic called these &lsquo;story breakdowns&rsquo; and &lsquo;epics&rsquo;, respectively). This gave the team the ability to take a guess at the project and design approach. </p>

